title: JavaScript
section:
I'm still not sure about JavaScript. It's a very powerful language that has been around for a long time... (over 20 years!), but I still don't like writing, debugging and testing it. It is becoming more and more popular, browser compatibility is getting better and don't get me wrong the finished result can be astonishing. Therefore I definitely feel the pressure to learn a JavaScript framework, but which one? Until there is a winner of "Best JavaScript Framework" I feel like whichever position I was going to take would require a different framework from what I've learned.

I have dappled in VueJS quite a bit, but as it so long between the projects that need JavaScript, I will never feel confident writing it from memory in my current situation. The key word in that sentence was need, a lot of projects I write do not need JavaScript. Yes it would be nice to write every form in VueJS so it's all flashy and smooth but it will always takes so much longer to write and then test, it is not worth it most of the time. I recently had a Junior Developer join the team, he considers himself a "JQuery expect" so he thought it was easier to write everything using it (AJAX everywhere), but I had to sit him down and explain that the JavaScript he had written could have been written with 2 lines of code instead of 50. Therefore the team will have to maintain that code or completely rewrite it, i.e. more code = bad. But there cases where JavaScript is required, especially now Adobe Flash is dead, so I will try try and form my opinions on JavaScript frameworks but until then I'm in limbo.

 

UPDATE (2019-04-21):
I have rewritten my personal website using VueJS instead of PHP, making it 100% static as well.

title: SOLID Principles
section:
I love SOLID Principles! When I was first learning to use Laravel, the software team decided to look at SOLID Principles as part of that experience. It was definitely a steep learning curve as we hadn't even ventured into using interfaces before, but learning the SOLID Principles meant it all fit into place. I remember watching a Laracasts series on SOLID Principles and it all made so much sense. I must admit, I don't always follow them, all the time but I try to code using these rules where it is possible to do so.

S: Single Responsibility Principle

This principle is probably the one I use the most. I like splitting code into separate classes and in the end most of them turn into a class with one method with a few lines of code. A member of my team asked why some code was written using single responsibility principle and the other just using one repository class, I said that one set of code was written by myself and the other written by someone else (who has left the team), guess which one they thought had used single responsibility classes? ME!

O: Open-Closed Principle

Open for extension and closed for modification using abstractions. Not everything fits this rule in the real world unfortunately but I endeavour to try.

L: Liskov Substitution Principle

This is probably my favourite principle, using interfaces and making sure the data entered and returned matches other classes implementing the same interface. I think since PHP 7.0 has been released with type declarations and return types it makes it a lot easier to follow this principle. On a side note it also makes it easier to read the code.

I: Interface Segregation Principle

Clients should not be forced to implement interfaces they do not use. Robert C. Martin

I don't think about this rule as much and I am not sure why. When I refreshed my knowledge the other day (re-watched a Laracasts series) I thought of some recent examples where I should have used it and hadn't, so there will be some refactoring in my future.

D: Dependency Inversion Principle

This principle is harder to understand but on the Laracasts they used a great example:

An electric socket (interface) belongs to the house (high level) and not an object that plugs into the electrical socket, i.e. a lamp (low level). We can have lots of lamps but if a lamp comes with a incompatible electric socket, it will not be up to the house to change all it's sockets but the responsibility of the lamp.

title: #bobthepanda
section:
I really like Giant Pandas, my Nan got me a Panda cuddly toy (Pandy) for my fifth birthday and I have been obsessed ever since. It's one of those things that if someone doesn't know what to get me for my birthday they will just get me a Panda of some kind and I will be very happy. A few years ago I got to go see a couple of real Pandas in Edinburgh and it was amazing. 

Now I try and take my pocket sized Panda called Bob with me and try and take photos with Bob in the frame. It's like a selfie but with a very small Panda instead of myself. We have been all over the country, taking pictures. I definitely get funny looks when I leave Bob and move back to take a picture. It is an ongoing series that has produced some pretty good photos (mostly funny). I have put them on Google Photos so you can take a look:

title: Visual Studio Code
section:
The last couple of days I have been using Visual Studio Code as my IDE for my personal work. At work I use PHPStorm so I have just continued to use that at home, but I have been hearing a lot about Code and decided to give it a try. I have discovered lots of annoying issues as this IDE is not built for PHP development specifically (like PHPStorm) but as I haven't been doing overly complicated code it seems OK. The most annoying thing at the moment is finding out it doesn't do something, then having to look for an extension and losing track of what you were actually trying to achieve. I am slowly getting more and more features configured but it is taking a while.

Therefore, I'm creating these lists in hope I can resolve some of my issues by Googling or finding some good extensions. I am keeping an open mind and will continue to use it at home as I believe it is becoming more widely used throughout the industry.

Pros

  • Free
  • Open source
  • Loads of extensions from the community (which are also really easy to install and remove)
  • Fast
  • Clean interface
  • Loads of themes available
  • Support of a lot of different languages
  • Better VueJS support
  • GIT support out of the box

Further Investigation Needed

  • Refactoring when moving namespaces
  • Importing classes
  • Automatically populating the namespace on file creation
  • Auto-complete variable after dependency injection (with private properties)
  • Display different icons for classes, interfaces and traits
  • Go to declaration
  • Duplicate line
  • XDebug
  • PHPUnit

Discovered

  • PHP intellisense
  • Manage snippets
  • Keymapping
  • User settings
  • Terminal
  • Git
  • VueJS
  • Themes
  • Markdown
    • Install extension: https://github.com/DavidAnson/vscode-markdownlint
  • .env support
    • Install extension: https://github.com/mikestead/vscode-dotenv
  • SFTP for deployment
    • Install extension: https://github.com/liximomo/vscode-sftp
    • Type "SFTP" into the commands search for all options

title: Continuous Integration
section:
Travis CI

I have started implementing Travis CI for V1 of my personal website, to build, test and hopefully deploy the code every time I commit to the GIT repository. The reason I chose Travis CI was that it seems easy to use with GitHub repositories and I don't have to host my own service like you do with Jenkins. It was very easy to create a Travis CI account and integrate it with GitHub then it was just a matter of Googling configuration examples to try.

So far I have successfully configured Travis CI to build the website and run my unit tests. But there is still two things left to do, run feature and browser tests and also deploy the code using SFTP. The SFTP deployment is proving difficult due to an ongoing bug with Ubuntu: https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/curl/+bug/311029. Unfortunately my web hosting only supports SFTP so I will probably have to move my website to get this working.

 

UPDATE (2018-12-01): Unit, feature and browser tests are all now configured and running. I had to give up on the deployment as I can quite easily do that manually for now, until I get better hosting.

This is my final .travis.yml configuration: https://github.com/ellllllen/personal-website/blob/master/.travis.yml

title: Chatbot
section:
So I purchased a book that was supposed to help me build a Chatbot. After 10 minutes of reading I realised this wasn't for me so I took the basics of the book and realised I could do what I wanted by using the online docs for BotMan: https://botman.io/

BotMan is pretty cool, it is a framework for creating a chatbot with PHP. There are loads of drivers available including Amazon Alexa and Slack but the one I needed was the Web driver.

For a project I wanted to build a Chatbot and integrate it into V1 of my personal website. The hardest thing was that the docs encourage you to use BotMan Studio, which is basically BotMan built into Laravel, but being as I already had my website and wanted to integrate BotMan into it. It became challenging to understand the routing and the various components I needed, but I managed to get it up and running!

It takes your name and will tell you a joke :)

All my commits are on my GitHib repo: https://github.com/ellllllen/personal-website/commit/4b69378b7c878ef0a99db4b65db0a39acb62b521

This is a little snippet of it working, again it was more about coding this than the final result.

title: VueJS Portfolio
section:
I decided to rewrite my personal website using VueJS. There was a few reasons for this, first I wanted more experience in coding VueJS and secondly, my website hosting and domain were expiring. I knew about free static site hosting like GitHub Pages and Netlify so thought I would give that a go instead.
I actually started by using Nuxt, but after creating a very crude home page, I decided to go back to basics and just use VueJS instead. Using a framework like Nuxt is fine but I wasn't really learning VueJS, which is what I set out to do.
I have how recreated most of the functionality of my PHP version of this website. Evently I will update V1 so both versions are displaying the same data.

So I have used Netlify to build and deploy V2, it is hosted here: https://ellen-portfolio.netlify.com/. It was so easy (almost too easy)!
